SHA-256 implementation (sha256.c / sha256.h)
Author: Brad Conte (brad AT bradconte.com)
Upstream: https://github.com/B-Con/crypto-algorithms

This code is released into the public domain free of any restrictions.
The author requests acknowledgement if the code is used, but does not
require it. This code is provided free of any liability and without any
quality claims by the author.

Local modification: the single `#include <memory.h>` in sha256.c (a legacy,
non-standard header alias) was changed to the standard `#include <string.h>`
so the file compiles unchanged under glibc, the mingw-w64 sysroot, and the
macOS SDK. `memset` — the only symbol used from it — is declared by both.

NOTE: this is a plain integrity hash. Per the upstream README it is NOT a
side-channel-resistant implementation; it is used here only to re-verify the
digest of a locally staged, already-authenticated update artifact immediately
before the atomic swap, which needs collision/preimage integrity, not secrecy.
